---

<section id="how-to-calculate" class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12 md:py-16">
  <div class="space-y-12">
    <!-- How to Calculate -->
    <article class="prose prose-slate max-w-none">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-heading mb-4 flex items-center gap-2">
        <span class="w-8 h-8 bg-primary/10 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-primary font-bold text-sm">1</span>
        How to Calculate Paint Coverage
      </h2>
      <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-6 shadow-sm border border-border">
        <p class="text-body mb-4">
          Calculating paint coverage is straightforward once you know the formula. First, measure your room's dimensions—length, width, and ceiling height in feet. Then calculate the wall area using this formula:
        </p>
        <div class="bg-light-gray rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-sm mb-4">
          Wall Area = 2 × (Length + Width) × Height
        </div>
        <p class="text-body mb-4">
          For example, a 12' × 14' room with 8' ceilings has:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-body space-y-1 mb-4">
          <li>Wall area: 2 × (12 + 14) × 8 = <strong>416 sq ft</strong></li>
          <li>After deducting a door (-21 sq ft) and 2 windows (-30 sq ft)</li>
          <li>Net paintable area: <strong>365 sq ft</strong></li>
        </ul>
        <p class="text-body mb-4">
          Standard paint covers about 400 square feet per gallon. With two coats, you'd need approximately <strong>2 gallons</strong> for this room.
        </p>
        <p class="text-body text-sm">
          Ready to buy supplies? Check out our <a href="#affiliate-section" class="text-primary hover:underline font-medium">recommended paint supplies</a> or <a href="#lead-section" class="text-primary hover:underline font-medium">get free quotes from local painters</a>.
        </p>
      </div>
    </article>

    <!-- Tips for Accuracy -->
    <article id="tips">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-heading mb-4 flex items-center gap-2">
        <span class="w-8 h-8 bg-primary/10 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-primary font-bold text-sm">2</span>
        Tips for Accurate Paint Estimates
      </h2>
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm border border-border">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-heading mb-2">Measure Twice</h3>
          <p class="text-body text-sm">
            Double-check your measurements before purchasing. It's easier to buy extra than to make multiple trips to the store.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm border border-border">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-heading mb-2">Account for Texture</h3>
          <p class="text-body text-sm">
            Textured walls absorb more paint. If your walls have knockdown, orange peel, or other textures, add 15-20% to your estimate.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm border border-border">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-heading mb-2">Consider Color Changes</h3>
          <p class="text-body text-sm">
            Going from dark to light? You may need 3 coats or a tinted primer. Light to dark usually needs standard 2 coats.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm border border-border">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-heading mb-2">Don't Forget Trim</h3>
          <p class="text-body text-sm">
            Baseboards, door frames, and crown molding add up. Budget about 1 quart per 100 linear feet of trim.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </article>

    <!-- When to Use Primer -->
    <article id="primer">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-heading mb-4 flex items-center gap-2">
        <span class="w-8 h-8 bg-primary/10 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-primary font-bold text-sm">3</span>
        When to Use Primer
      </h2>
      <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-6 shadow-sm border border-border">
        <p class="text-body mb-4">
          Primer isn't always necessary, but it's essential in these situations:
        </p>
        <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-3">
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3 p-3 bg-light-gray rounded-lg">
            <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-accent mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7" />
            </svg>
            <span class="text-sm text-body"><strong>New drywall</strong> - absorbs paint unevenly without primer</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3 p-3 bg-light-gray rounded-lg">
            <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-accent mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7" />
            </svg>
            <span class="text-sm text-body"><strong>Stained surfaces</strong> - primer blocks water stains and smoke damage</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3 p-3 bg-light-gray rounded-lg">
            <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-accent mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7" />
            </svg>
            <span class="text-sm text-body"><strong>Dark to light colors</strong> - helps achieve true color in fewer coats</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3 p-3 bg-light-gray rounded-lg">
            <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-accent mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7" />
            </svg>
            <span class="text-sm text-body"><strong>Glossy surfaces</strong> - primer helps paint adhere better</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3 p-3 bg-light-gray rounded-lg">
            <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-accent mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7" />
            </svg>
            <span class="text-sm text-body"><strong>High-humidity rooms</strong> - mold-resistant primer protects bathrooms</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3 p-3 bg-light-gray rounded-lg">
            <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-accent mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7" />
            </svg>
            <span class="text-sm text-body"><strong>Previously unpainted wood</strong> - seals and prevents tannin bleed</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="text-body mt-4 text-sm">
          <strong>Pro tip:</strong> Many premium paints now include primer. Check the label—you might be able to skip this step. Not sure which to buy? Browse our <a href="#affiliate-section" class="text-primary hover:underline">recommended paint products</a>.
        </p>
      </div>
    </article>

    <!-- PaintPro Insights: Ohio & Midwest Regional Tips (Information Gain Section) -->
    <article id="regional-insights" class="relative">
      <div class="absolute -top-2 left-4 bg-accent text-white text-xs font-bold px-3 py-1 rounded-full">
        PaintPro Insights
      </div>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-heading mb-4 flex items-center gap-2 pt-4">
        <span class="w-8 h-8 bg-accent/10 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-accent font-bold text-sm">4</span>
        Ohio & Midwest Climate Painting Tips
      </h2>
      <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-accent/5 to-primary/5 rounded-xl p-6 shadow-sm border border-accent/20">
        <p class="text-body mb-4">
          <strong>Based on our regional data:</strong> Painting conditions in Ohio and the Midwest require special considerations due to humidity fluctuations and seasonal temperature swings. Here's what the generic paint calculators won't tell you:
        </p>

        <div class="space-y-4">
          <!-- Humidity Impact -->
          <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-4 border border-border">
            <h3 class="font-semibold text-heading mb-2 flex items-center gap-2">
              <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-accent" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M3 15a4 4 0 004 4h9a5 5 0 10-.1-9.999 5.002 5.002 0 10-9.78 2.096A4.001 4.001 0 003 15z" />
              </svg>
              Summer Humidity Factor
            </h3>
            <p class="text-body text-sm mb-2">
              Ohio summers average <strong>70-80% relative humidity</strong>. During July and August, interior paint requires <strong>25-40% longer drying time</strong> between coats compared to manufacturer specifications.
            </p>
            <div class="bg-light-gray rounded p-3 text-sm">
              <strong>PaintPro Recommendation:</strong> Wait 4-6 hours between coats (vs. standard 2-4 hours) when humidity exceeds 65%. Use a dehumidifier to maintain 40-50% indoor humidity for optimal results.
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Temperature Swings -->
          <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-4 border border-border">
            <h3 class="font-semibold text-heading mb-2 flex items-center gap-2">
              <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-accent" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M12 3v1m0 16v1m9-9h-1M4 12H3m15.364 6.364l-.707-.707M6.343 6.343l-.707-.707m12.728 0l-.707.707M6.343 17.657l-.707.707" />
              </svg>
              Spring/Fall Temperature Swings
            </h3>
            <p class="text-body text-sm mb-2">
              Midwest spring and fall can see <strong>30°F+ temperature swings</strong> within 24 hours. Paint applied when temperatures drop below 50°F overnight may not cure properly, leading to adhesion failure.
            </p>
            <div class="bg-light-gray rounded p-3 text-sm">
              <strong>PaintPro Recommendation:</strong> Check the 48-hour forecast before painting. Ensure temperatures stay above 50°F (10°C) for at least 24 hours after application. Best months: May-June and September.
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Basement Considerations -->
          <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-4 border border-border">
            <h3 class="font-semibold text-heading mb-2 flex items-center gap-2">
              <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-accent" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M3 12l2-2m0 0l7-7 7 7M5 10v10a1 1 0 001 1h3m10-11l2 2m-2-2v10a1 1 0 01-1 1h-3m-6 0a1 1 0 001-1v-4a1 1 0 011-1h2a1 1 0 011 1v4a1 1 0 001 1m-6 0h6" />
              </svg>
              Ohio Basement Paint Calculations
            </h3>
            <p class="text-body text-sm mb-2">
              Ohio homes frequently have <strong>high water tables</strong> causing basement moisture issues. Standard paint calculations don't account for the <strong>30% increased paint consumption</strong> on porous concrete block walls.
            </p>
            <div class="bg-light-gray rounded p-3 text-sm">
              <strong>PaintPro Recommendation:</strong> For basement walls, add 30% to your calculated amount and always use moisture-blocking primer. Consider waterproofing paint for areas below grade.
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Local Paint Store Insight -->
          <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-4 border border-border">
            <h3 class="font-semibold text-heading mb-2 flex items-center gap-2">
              <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-accent" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M9 5H7a2 2 0 00-2 2v12a2 2 0 002 2h10a2 2 0 002-2V7a2 2 0 00-2-2h-2M9 5a2 2 0 002 2h2a2 2 0 002-2M9 5a2 2 0 012-2h2a2 2 0 012 2m-6 9l2 2 4-4" />
              </svg>
              Regional Product Availability
            </h3>
            <p class="text-body text-sm">
              Northeast Ohio Sherwin-Williams stores report that <strong>low-VOC interior latex</strong> performs best for the region's humidity. Ask for products specifically formulated for high-humidity environments—they typically cost 10-15% more but provide better coverage and durability.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="text-body mt-6 text-sm text-center">
          Need professional help? <a href="#lead-section" class="text-accent hover:underline font-semibold">Get free quotes from local Ohio painters</a> who understand these regional factors.
        </p>
      </div>
    </article>
  </div>
</section>

